  "tradeoffs-failure-monitoring": {
    id: "tradeoffs-failure-monitoring",
    intuition: "Every design decision has a trade-off. Strong candidates name trade-offs explicitly. They also think proactively about failure modes — how does this break, and what's the mitigation?",
    technicalDetail: "Trade-off framework: latency vs consistency (caching makes reads fast but stale), scalability vs complexity (sharding scales writes but adds cross-shard query complexity), cost vs durability (3 replicas vs 1), strong vs eventual consistency (CAP). Failure modes to cover: single point of failure (every non-HA component), cascading failure (one slow service blocks all), data loss (what happens if a node crashes mid-write), network partition (split-brain scenarios), thundering herd (cache stampede after outage). Mitigations: circuit breakers, bulkheads, backpressure, idempotency, graceful degradation.",
    tradeoffs: [
      "Naming trade-offs vs hiding them: being explicit about trade-offs shows senior-level thinking; hiding them looks naive",
      "Defending your choice vs being open: defend with data, stay open to pushback — 'I chose X, here's why, but Y would be better if Z'",
      "Proactive vs reactive: mention failure modes before interviewer asks — shows production mindset",
      "Over-engineering mitigation: every failure mode doesn't need a fix — triage by probability × impact",
    ],
    realWorldExample: "Example trade-off statement (good): 'I chose write-through caching here. The trade-off is slower writes — each write hits both cache and DB. But for a product catalog that's read 100× more than written, the read speedup outweighs the write penalty. I'd revisit this if write SLA becomes stricter.'",
    interviewQuestion: "What are the main failure modes in the notification system you designed?",
    modelAnswer: "1) Queue backlog: consumer lag → notifications delayed/dropped. Mitigation: alert on consumer lag, autoscale workers. 2) Push token expired: silent delivery failure. Mitigation: handle APNs/FCM error codes, remove expired tokens. 3) Duplicate delivery: at-least-once queue + retry = duplicate. Mitigation: idempotency key, dedup in delivery service. 4) Thundering herd: all users receive notification simultaneously → massive DB read spike. Mitigation: stagger delivery, rate-limit by cohort.",
    commonMistakes: [
      "Stating trade-offs without context ('cache is faster' — everyone knows that) vs real trade-offs ('cache introduces eventual consistency — user may see stale product price')",
      "Not discussing the failure that your chosen design introduces — every design introduces new failure modes, not just removes them",
      "Presenting only one design without any alternatives — makes it seem you couldn't think of another approach",
    ],
    memoryTrick: "For each component ask: what happens if this fails? what happens if this is slow? what happens if this returns stale/wrong data? 3 failure modes per component covers 90% of cases.",
    relatedConcepts: ["deep-dives", "circuit-breaker", "observability", "45-minute-clock"],
    cheatSheetLine: "Name trade-offs explicitly: latency/consistency, scale/complexity, cost/durability. Failure modes: SPOF, cascade, data loss, stampede. Mitigate by probability × impact.",
  },

