  "8-scaling-moves": {
    id: "8-scaling-moves",
    intuition: "When asked 'how would you scale this?', these 8 moves cover 95% of scaling solutions. Apply them in order of increasing complexity — exhaust simple moves before reaching for hard ones.",
    technicalDetail: "1) Scale Up: bigger machine (more CPU/RAM). Zero code changes, cheap at small scale. Ceiling hit fast. 2) Add Cache: Redis for repeated reads. Usually 10× read reduction. Most impactful early move. 3) Read Replicas: multiple DB readers. Scale reads ≠ writes. 4) CDN: offload static + cacheable content to edge. 5) Async Queue: decouple heavy work from request path. Smooth write spikes. 6) Horizontal Scale: more app servers behind load balancer. App must be stateless. 7) Database Sharding: split writes and storage across multiple DB instances. Complex. 8) Microservices Decomposition: independent scaling per component. Highest complexity.",
    tradeoffs: [
      "Moves 1-4: low complexity, large gains — should be exhausted before moves 5-8",
      "Caching (move 2): most impactful per complexity unit — should almost always be first architectural addition",
      "Async queue (move 5): improves throughput and resilience — adds eventual consistency, more components to operate",
      "Sharding (move 7): solves write bottleneck — complex joins, distributed transactions, hotspot management",
    ],
    realWorldExample: "Stack Overflow (2022): handles 1.4B pageviews/month on 9 web servers + 2 SQL servers + Redis cache. They've applied moves 1-3 (powerful servers, Redis, SQL read replica) but never sharded. Simple ≠ bad. StackOverflow's architecture is celebrated as an example that boring technology + good caching scales further than most systems need.",
    interviewQuestion: "Your database is the bottleneck at 50K QPS. Walk me through your scaling approach.",
    modelAnswer: "First: profile query plans. Likely missing an index. Add index → often 10-100× query speedup, no architecture change. Next: Redis cache for top queries — if 80% of reads are for the same 1K items, cache reduces DB load by 80%. Add read replicas for remaining read traffic. If write QPS is the bottleneck, consider separating write-heavy tables. Last resort: horizontal sharding — but check if read replicas + cache solved it first.",
    commonMistakes: [
      "Jumping to sharding as the first scaling move — sharding is move 7 of 8; cache and read replicas usually solve the problem",
      "Adding queue without addressing the root bottleneck — async queue hides the problem temporarily; the consumer still hits the same DB",
      "Not identifying the actual bottleneck — CPU? disk I/O? network? DB query? Each has a different fix",
    ],
    memoryTrick: "SCALE UP: Scale up, Cache, Async, Loadbalance/replicate, Evolve DB (shard), Unbundle (microservices), Precompute, CDN. Apply in order.",
    relatedConcepts: ["scalability", "caching", "sharding", "message-queues"],
    cheatSheetLine: "Order: scale up → cache → read replicas → CDN → async queue → horizontal scale → sharding → microservices. Exhaust cheaper moves first. Cache = highest ROI per complexity.",
  },

  "what-breaks-first": {
    id: "what-breaks-first",
    intuition: "Under load, systems break in predictable ways. Knowing what breaks first — and in what order — lets you proactively design mitigations and lets you answer 'what are the failure modes of your design?'",
    technicalDetail: "Failure order under load: 1) Database connections exhausted (no connection pool). 2) Slow queries cause connection pile-up. 3) Cache miss storm (cold start or expiry). 4) Queue consumer lag grows, queue fills memory/disk. 5) Downstream service times out → upstream threads block → upstream memory fills → OOM. 6) CPU saturates on app servers. 7) Disk I/O saturates on DB. Watch for: N+1 queries (loop issue), missing indexes (full table scan under load), unbounded queues (memory leak), synchronous blocking calls to slow services (thread starvation).",
    tradeoffs: [
      "Optimistic design (assume nothing fails): fast to build, breaks catastrophically under real load",
      "Defensive design (assume everything fails): robust, adds code complexity and latency for happy path",
      "Connection pool too small: bottleneck but simple fix. Too large: DB OOM from too many connections",
      "Unbounded queue: absorbs burst — but if consumers can't keep up, queue grows until OOM or disk full",
    ],
    realWorldExample: "AWS re:Invent post-mortem pattern: most prod incidents follow the same sequence. Traffic spike → DB connections exhausted → timeout → request queue grows → retry storm → DB load doubles → DB host CPU 100% → DB becomes unresponsive → full outage. The fix: connection pool + circuit breaker + rate limiting, applied in that order.",
    interviewQuestion: "What would be the first thing to break in the design you just described under 10× traffic?",
    modelAnswer: "Walk through each layer: App servers: stateless, auto-scale → handles spike. Load balancer: HA, auto-scales → handles spike. Redis: 100K ops/sec → handles spike. DB: here's the issue. 10× traffic = 10K QPS → DB at 100K QPS with cache hits, but cold cache or write-heavy = DB at 50K QPS → near limit. First break: DB connections exhausted. Mitigation: PgBouncer connection pooler, add read replicas, cache critical queries.",
    commonMistakes: [
      "Saying 'nothing breaks' — every design has a bottleneck; finding it is the point of the question",
      "Only identifying one failure mode — walk through each layer systematically",
      "Identifying the failure without naming the mitigation — interviewers want both",
    ],
    memoryTrick: "DQAST: DB connections → Query slowness → Async queue lag → Service timeout cascade → Thread starvation. This is the failure order. Design mitigations for each.",
    relatedConcepts: ["circuit-breaker", "observability", "connection-pooling", "rate-limiting"],
    cheatSheetLine: "Failure order: DB connections → slow queries → cache stampede → queue backlog → timeout cascade. For each: identify trigger, identify mitigation. Always find the bottleneck.",
  },

